<!-- ═══ APPROACH ═══ -->
<section class="cs-section">
  <div class="cs-section-inner reveal">
    <h2 class="cs-section-heading">THE APPROACH</h2>
    <div class="cs-body">
      <p>I built Techtonic three times. Not because of poor planning — because the product changed underneath it. Each version was a response to a new product direction, new platform requirements, and new scale demands.</p>
      <p><strong>Version 1</strong> was a cleanup: audit everything, consolidate duplicates, establish base tokens and core components. It brought order to chaos but was designed for a product scope that soon expanded.</p>
      <p><strong>Version 2</strong> introduced platform-specific adaptations. iOS, Android, and web each got their own component sets that shared the same tokens but respected platform conventions. This version also introduced the icon library — 103 custom icons designed specifically for ZAR's product vocabulary.</p>
      <p><strong>Version 3</strong> was the system that shipped. It integrated with GitHub and Storybook, giving engineers a coded component library that mirrored Figma 1:1. Design tokens were synced between Figma and code. 37 Figma pages organized by component category, pattern, and platform. Full documentation for every component.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="cs-img-placeholder">
      <i class="ph-bold ph-image"></i>
      <span>Add screenshot — Techtonic Figma structure</span>
    </div>
    <div class="cs-img-placeholder">
      <i class="ph-bold ph-image"></i>
